  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 7 @ 2017/2018",
    "Question": {
      "content": "Two point parallel plate capacitors are identical except that one is filled with a dielectric material \\(\\epsilon_r\\) = 10.5 and the other is air filled. How much larger is the capacitance of dielectric filled capacitor than the air filled?",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "0.0095",
        "1.0095",
        "10.5",
        "11.5"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "10.5"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "The capacitance with a dielectric is \\( C = \\epsilon_r C_0 \\), where \\( C_0 \\) is the capacitance with air (\\(\\epsilon_r = 1\\)). The ratio of the dielectric-filled capacitance to the air-filled capacitance is \\(\\epsilon_r = 10.5\\), so it is 10.5 times larger."
    },
    "topic": [
      "Capacitors and Dielectrics",
      "Electric Fields",
      "Relative Permittivity"
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 9 @ 2017/2018",
    "Question": {
      "content": "A capacitor is to be built which will store enough energy to light a 50W energy bulb for 30mins. If available potential difference is 200V, what capacitance is needed?",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "90F",
        "45F",
        "6F",
        "9F"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "90F"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "Energy stored in a capacitor is \\( E = \\frac{1}{2} C V^2 \\). Energy required = 50W \\times 1800s = 90000J. Thus, \\( 90000 = \\frac{1}{2} C (200)^2 \\), so \\( C = \\frac{2 \\times 90000}{40000} = 90F \\)."
    },
    "topic": [
      "Capacitors and Dielectrics",
      "Electric Potential",
      "Electric Potential Energy"
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 10 @ 2017/2018",
    "Question": {
      "content": "A capacitor is charged by 9.0V battery and receives a charge of 3.0\\(\\mu\\)C. What is the capacitance of the capacitor?",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "0.33\\(\\mu\\)F",
        "27\\(\\mu\\)F",
        "0.30\\(\\mu\\)F",
        "It cannot be determined"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "\\(0.33\\muF \\)"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "Capacitance \\( C = \\frac{Q}{V} \\), where \\( Q = 3.0 \\times 10^{-6}C \\) and \\( V = 9.0V \\). Thus, \\( C = \\frac{3.0 \\times 10^{-6}}{9.0} = 0.333 \\times 10^{-6}F = 0.33\\mu F \\)."
    },
    "topic": [
      "Capacitors and Dielectrics",
      "Capacitance",
      "Electrostatics",
      "Electric Potential"
    ]
  },
